	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Malawiâ€™s agricultural trade policy and the IEPA</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The sections of the WTO May 2010 Malawi Trade Policy Review (TPR) dealing with agriculture and agricultural trade policy, provide some insights into the Malawian governmentâ€™s concerns over the provisions of the interim EPA (IEPA). The TPR highlights the heavy dependence of the Malawian economy on agriculture, its vulnerability to drought and acute food scarcity, its continued use of tariffs as a trade policy tools (with average agricultural tariffs of 17.3% compared to an average of 13.1% overall). It also notes the use of a range of non-tariff measures in the agricultural sector, including:</p>
<ul>

<li>the use of non-automatic import licences for infant industry protection (sugar, maize and milk) and public health purposes;</li>

<li>the use of export licences for maize and maize products, tea, cotton, soya beans, rice and unmanufactured tobacco;</li>

<li>the periodic use of export bans for maize and rice on food security grounds.</li>

</ul>
<p>The TPR highlights the governmentâ€™s core food-security-related Farm Input Subsidy Programme, which is intended to insulate farmers from escalating input costs and hence stimulate domestic maize production on which both the urban and rural poor depend. It however notes the mounting fiscal burden that this programme is imposing on the public finances (almost 5% of GDP), and the extent to which this is squeezing out â€˜investments with potentially higher long-term rates of return than fertiliser subsidies, such as agricultural research irrigation or measures to reduce maize crop losses.â€™ It stresses the importance of diversifying production and exports, given the precarious macroeconomic situation in the country.</p><p>More generally the WTO review notes the complexity of Malawiâ€™s tariff schedule and the need to rationalise and simplify it.</p><p>These complexities and difficulties provide the background against which Malawiâ€™s government has called on the EC to provide â€˜a clear assuranceâ€™ on how the proposed IEPA will benefit Malawi. The most recent exchange on these issues occurred at the two-day seminar convened in association with the EC â€˜[to] discuss the role of Malawi in the EPA within the Eastern and Southern African region.â€™ According to press reports of the meeting, Trade Minister Eunice Kazembe highlighted how Malawi was â€˜a landlocked and least developed country, with poor public infrastructure, low labour productivity, inadequate technological capacity and unreliable public utilitiesâ€™ and underlined the importance of addressing these challenges before full liberalisation. Other Malawian speakers at the meeting stressed how the IEPA â€˜will have the effect of undermining Malawiâ€™s policy autonomyâ€™, possibly causing serious problems for the countryâ€™s economic development. Particular concerns were expressed about the customs revenue losses that will follow the full implementation of the IEPA (see companion article â€˜Agriculture and the fiscal impact of EPAsâ€™ for an exploration of these issues).</p><p>In response, EC representatives sought to reiterate the EUâ€™s commitment to â€˜working with the Malawian government to meet the goals it set for itself within its economic development programme,â€™ including helping to address â€˜customs revenue losses due to the phasing in of EPA provisionsâ€™. However, according to press reports the head of the EC trade team attending the meeting expressed â€˜frustration and impatience with Malawiâ€™, noting that after seven years the EPA negotiations â€˜are not progressing as we would wishâ€™. He argued that â€˜it is now time to take a decision on whether there is a clear way forward together and, if so, under what timelines.â€™</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>IPS</i>, â€˜Malawi stands firm on conditions for signing EPAâ€™, 28 July 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=52306" target="_self">http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=52306</a></p><p>WTO, Trade Policy Review: Malawi, 5 May 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp331_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp331_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The WTO TPR implicitly identifies a number of areas where the government of Malawi uses trade policy tools to promote its underlying food security and agricultural development policy objectives, which could be brought into question by certain of the non-tariff provisions included in a number of the IEPAs. In this context there would appear to be a need for a systematic review of the appropriate and affordable alternative agricultural policy and agricultural trade policy tools which the government of Malawi could use to promote its underlying food security and agricultural development objectives, in view of the envisaged IEPA commitments on the use of export licences, import licences and infant industry protection measures.</p><p>In this context, it should be noted that the EU commonly sets in place alternative policy measures before dismantling the use of traditional trade policy tools. In the case of export subsidies, for example, the EC has a commitment to the abolition of export subsidies as a final policy objective, and the shift over to direct aid payments has considerably reduced the need to use this policy tool (with total expenditures falling dramatically). However export subsidies continue to be used, sometimes at increased levels, where market developments so require (e.g. in the pig-meat sector in recent years).</p><p>This pragmatic approach, whereby alternative policy measures to attain underlying policy objectives are firmly in place before abandoning the use of traditional trade policy tools, would appear to be relevant in the case of Malawi, whose economy â€˜is heavily dependent on agriculture and exports of primary commodities.â€™</p>
		</div>
		
